The IMF needs more Lagarde.
Davos — Lagarde has said she is open to serving another five years as Managing Director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should stay in office.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than she, and the IMF Board of Governors should give her the opportunity to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, assuming leadership of an institution in deep crisis.
The global financial crash of 2008 and its economic aftermath severely damaged the credibility of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington Consensus."
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF restore its reputation.
Many eyes turned to her personal qualities — as they should.
She is candid, strong, warm, and touching.
Officials from various countries (often meeting her in delicate circumstances) have expressed that she dares to speak out about difficult realities, while also being a sensitive listener.
These are important qualities for a leader of an institution that must negotiate the terms of an agreement rather than dictate everything.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed to be restructured, or alternatively, firewalls had to be established to prevent financial contagion. The advice was unwelcome, but Europeans complied nonetheless.
Similarly, she strongly advocated for IMF support to some countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — emphasizing that this is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
The IMF is not particularly good at innovation and is usually not full of passion.
Lagarde began to change this.
In this process, she gave this institution, which often prescribed harsh remedies, a more humane face.
For example, helping manage the refugee crisis in the Middle East was originally not within the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF revised the program to enable the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist those displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over one million people reside in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak hit West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF in using its available funds to provide debt relief to countries affected by the crisis, enabling them to improve the salaries of doctors and nurses—this was the first time the IMF had used its capital in such a way.
Moreover, Lagarde recognizes that the world today faces three of the most important challenges and is taking action to address them.
First, she strongly advocated for more women to join the workforce, and she herself serves as a role model demonstrating the value of women in leadership positions.
In countries ranging from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop squandering such a vast human resource — and thereby realize their economic potential.
Secondly, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a basic issue of fairness.
The IMF's research emphasizes that there is a direct link between reducing the wealth gap and increasing economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to demonstrate this, but its stature makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde has personally been committed to promoting this point, which is key to the increased urgency.
Third, Lagarde has played a significant role in helping the world understand the full impact of technological change, some of which will have frighteningly disruptive consequences.
For example, automation will continue to improve efficiency in manufacturing and reduce its costs, but it also means that the number of jobs generated by economic growth will be less than in the past.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde made the IMF the core of this effort.
Critics would say it is time for representatives from developing countries to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th European to hold this position consecutively, and such a privilege for Europe is hard to justify in today's world.
Some people also argue that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not been fully effective, which demonstrates that the IMF has become disconnected from the general public.
Others will point out that she faces charges related to financial scandals in France, which would distract her from her work at the IMF.
Critics believe that the IMF must never again be distracted by similar scandals, following the controversy surrounding its former head, Dominique Strauss-Kahn.
Let's analyze these objections one by one.
The IMF (as well as the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the United States.
But the aim of ending this Western privilege is to make the leader selection process based on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best candidate for the IMF's leadership, and the emerging powers such as the BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) have not jointly nominated an alternative candidate.
Having a European serve as the IMF's Managing Director may also have been a favorable factor in the IMF's decision late last year to include the Chinese yuan in the currency basket that determines the value of Special Drawing Rights.
In addition, Lagarde ultimately convinced both the Republican and Democratic parties in the U.S. Congress to approve IMF governance reforms, demonstrating impressive political flexibility. These reforms not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal for containing financial crises but also more accurately reflected the evolving dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRIC countries have now entered the top ten shareholder ranks of the IMF.
Regarding the issue of Greece, Lagarde made some blunt — which some considered inappropriate — remarks of her own style last year.
But she is certainly not the culprit responsible for the economic suffering of the Greeks. Her tenure at the IMF clearly demonstrated that, in the history of the IMF, no Managing Director has ever done so much to lead the Fund in its efforts to alleviate the suffering of people in crisis.
Finally, the charges against Lagarde in France were opposed by the French Chief Prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most only slightly involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven that she is exactly the kind of leader committed to adapting the IMF for the 21st century.
She deserves the opportunity to see things through from start to finish.
